        "body": "Job postings outlive their usefulness constantly: the role gets filled, the headcount gets pulled, the requisition changes shape. What usually happens next is a 404 page, a form that still accepts applications for a job that no longer exists, or a listing that just sits there looking abandoned on the third-party board where you first posted it. None of that reflects well on a company, and it wastes a candidate's time. When you close a role in Aster, its apply page updates itself to a clear, courteous notice that the position is no longer open, rather than breaking or vanishing. It also drops off the public job board automatically, so browsing candidates only ever see roles you're actually hiring for. Anyone who bookmarked the link, found it through an old social post, or was sent it late by a friend still gets a coherent experience instead of a broken one. It's a small detail, but it's often the last interaction a candidate has with your company, and it costs nothing to get it right instead of leaving a stale link live for months after the role closed."
