    "deepDive": [
      {
        "title": "See client-ready experience at a glance",
        "body": "Client-ready experience rarely announces itself in a job title. It shows up in the industries someone has actually served, the specific skills they've applied under pressure, and how much responsibility they carried at their seniority level. Aster parses every resume into structured data on all three, then scores each applicant against the actual requirements of the engagement, with plain-language reasons behind the score instead of a black-box number. A recruiter can see at a glance why one candidate ranks above another: three years advising retail clients on supply chain versus six months of adjacent exposure, a certification that matches the mandate versus one that doesn't. Skill and industry matching tolerates typos and synonyms, so \"SOX compliance\" and \"Sarbanes-Oxley\" surface the same people, and a candidate who wrote \"client-facing\" instead of \"client-ready\" isn't filtered out by accident. Duplicate applications from the same person across postings are merged into one record automatically, so your team is comparing individuals, not the same candidate counted twice."
      },
      {
        "title": "Every partner asks from the same playbook",
        "body": "Ask five partners to interview the same candidate cold, and you'll get five different conversations, some probing technical depth, some spending the whole slot on rapport. That inconsistency makes it nearly impossible to compare candidates fairly, especially across a search that runs for weeks. Aster drafts interview questions specific to the role and the individual candidate's background, so a senior manager interviewing for a tax advisory role gets questions built around that candidate's actual industry exposure and the mandate's requirements, not a generic bank of behavioral prompts. Every interviewer walks in with the same structure to work from, which means the differences you see in the debrief are differences in the candidates, not differences in how each partner chose to run the room. Scheduling adds its own friction for busy, senior interviewers with packed calendars. Aster's self-scheduling lets candidates pick a slot directly and generates the Google Meet or Microsoft Teams link automatically, so getting a partner and a candidate into the same room takes one step instead of five emails."
      },
      {
        "title": "A decision you can defend",
        "body": "When a hiring decision gets questioned later, whether by a client, a managing partner, or the candidate themselves, \"the team liked them\" isn't much of an answer. Aster has every interviewer fill out a collaborative 1-4 scorecard right after their conversation, scoring the specific criteria that matter for the role rather than a vague overall impression. Those individual scores roll up automatically into one team score, so you can see not just the average but where the panel agreed and where it split. If two interviewers rate a candidate a 4 on client communication and one rates them a 2, that split is visible and worth a conversation before an offer goes out, not a disagreement that quietly disappears into a single summary. For firms where staffing decisions carry real financial weight, being able to show exactly what each interviewer scored, on what basis, and how the team arrived at a final call turns a hiring decision into a documented, defensible process rather than a judgment call nobody can reconstruct afterward."
      },
      {
        "title": "Your best candidates, ready for the next search",
        "body": "Professional services hiring is rarely a single event. The same skill sets and industry backgrounds you need this quarter usually come around again next quarter, on a different engagement with a different start date. The candidate who made the final round last time but lost out to someone with slightly more specific sector experience is often exactly who you need six months later, if you can find them again. Aster keeps every applicant, referral, and alumnus in a searchable talent pool rather than letting them disappear into a closed requisition. Search that pool by skill, industry, or seniority the moment a new engagement opens, with the same typo and synonym tolerance you get on live applications, and source-tracked apply links show you which channel, a referral, a job board, your own careers site, brought each person in originally. Instead of starting sourcing from zero and paying to re-find people you've already vetted, your first move on a new search can be reopening a conversation with someone who already knows your firm and already impressed you once."
      },
      {
        "title": "Sensitive searches, handled carefully",
        "body": "Professional services firms often run searches that need to stay quiet, replacing someone still in the seat, staffing a confidential client engagement, or weighing internal transfers alongside external candidates. Aster's role-based access means only the people who need to see a candidate's profile can see it, so a partner leading a discreet search isn't relying on everyone in the firm to just not mention it. Every rich, shareable candidate profile carries the resume, scores, interview notes, and scorecards in one place, viewable by the people who have access without forwarding attachments around over email. Underneath that, an audit trail records who viewed, moved, or scored each candidate and when, so if a decision is ever questioned, internally or by a client, there's a factual record of the process rather than a reconstruction from memory. For firms where hiring decisions and client confidentiality both carry weight, that combination of controlled access and a clear record isn't a compliance afterthought, it's part of how the search gets run properly from the start."
      }
    ],
